❓ WHY TWO DEQUES

Need:

- Current Window Minimum
- Current Window Maximum

Fast access chahiye.

Min Deque:
Front = smallest element

Max Deque:
Front = largest element

Therefore:

max - min

O(1) me mil jata hai.

⏱️ COMPLEXITY
Time  : O(N)

Reason:
- Har element max ek baar insert hota hai.
- Har element max ek baar remove hota hai.

Space : O(N)
(Worst case deques)

🎯 INTERVIEW POINT
- Condition:

  maxWindow - minWindow <= 2

- Min deque = increasing
- Max deque = decreasing

- Most important formula:

  count += (r - l + 1)

Why?

Current valid window:

[l ... r]

Agar length = 4

Toh r par end hone wale valid subarrays:

1 length
2 length
3 length
4 length

Total = 4

i.e.

r - l + 1

- This is a classic:
  "Count Subarrays + Sliding Window + Monotonic Deque" pattern.

#Code:

import java.util.*;

public class Solution {
    public long continuousSubarrays(int[] nums) {
      //You can code here

      ArrayDeque<Integer> min = new ArrayDeque<>();
      ArrayDeque<Integer> max = new ArrayDeque<>();
      long count = 0;

      int l = 0;
      int n = nums.length;
      for(int r=0; r<n; r++){
        //managing min deque
        while(!min.isEmpty() && min.getLast() > nums[r]){
          min.pollLast();
        }
        min.offerLast(nums[r]);

        //managing max deque
        while(!max.isEmpty() && max.getLast() < nums[r]){
          max.pollLast();
        }
        max.offerLast(nums[r]);

        //check if absolute difference is greater than 2
        while(max.peekFirst() - min.peekFirst() > 2){
          if(min.peekFirst() == nums[l]){
            min.pollFirst();
          }

          if(max.peekFirst() == nums[l]){
            max.pollFirst();
          }
          l++;
        }

        count += (long)(r-l+1);
      }
      return count;
       
    }
}
